-- Japan, Malaysia, S. Korea, Taiwan, Thailand: Asian Bond, Currency Preview
-- V. Ramakrishnan
-- 2010-06-27T21:43:24Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-27/japan-malaysia-s-korea-taiwan-thailand-asian-bond-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  will hold a
media briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo. The nation’s large-store
sales fell 2.9 percent in May after dropping 3.6 percent in
April, according to the median estimate from economists in a
Bloomberg News survey before the Ministry of Economy, Trade and
Industry reports the data at 8:50 a.m.  
 The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due June 2020
was 1.145 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 89.32 per dollar at 6:40 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 Malaysia: The central bank will sell 1 billion ringgit
($308 million) of 91-day Islamic notes and 1.5 billion ringgit
of 266-day notes today.  
 The yield on the 4.378 percent debt maturing in November
2019 was 3.95 percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The ringgit
was at 3.2508.  
 Philippines: The government will sell 3 billion pesos ($64
million) of 182-day bills and 3.5 billion pesos of 364-day bills
today. The yield on the 7.75 percent debt due in February 2020
was 7.67 percent, according to Philippine Dealing & Exchange
Corp. The peso was at 46.445 per dollar.  
 Singapore: The government will sell S$2.5 billion ($1.8
billion) of 2.5 percent two-year bonds today. It will also
auction S$3.6 billion of 91-day treasury bills.  
 The yield on the 3.25 percent notes due in September 2020
was 2.47 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.3868.  
 South Korea: The government will sell 800 billion won ($657
million) of 20-year bonds today. The yield on South Korea’s 4.50
percent bond due in March 2015 was 4.52 percent. The won was at
1,214.40.  
 Taiwan: The Council for Economic Planning and Development
will release the leading index for May today. The measure, a
gauge of economic conditions three months ahead, climbed 0.4
percent in April from the previous month.  
 The yield on the 1.375 percent bond maturing in March 2020
was 1.46 percent, according to Gretai Securities Market. The
Taiwan dollar traded at NT$32.18 per dollar.  
 Thailand: The government will sell 2 billion baht of ($61.7
million) 28-day and 4 billion baht each of 91- and 182-day bills
today. The yield on the 3.875 percent bond maturing in June 2019
was 3.18 percent. The baht was at 32.39.  
